# STRATEGY 2 — KEEP HERMES MERGEABLE

> **Pay code duplication if it means upstream files stay untouched.**

## NEVER modify (zero business coupling)

```
run_agent.py          cli.py              hermes_cli/main.py
agent/memory_manager.py
tools/file_operations.py    tools/file_tools.py    tools/terminal_tool.py
gateway/platforms/api_server.py
```

Memory isolation: `HERMES_HOME` ContextVar via `enter_user_context` — **not** `MemoryManager` edits.

## ALLOWED fork touchpoints (additive, ≤10 lines each)

`run_agent.py` (user_id propagation), `gateway/run.py` (WEB_CHAT), `hermes_state.py` (user_id filters), `toolsets.py` (`hermes-web-chat`). Full list: `CLAUDE.md`.

## Where new code goes

| Kind | Location |
|------|----------|
| SaaS control plane | `platform-api/` |
| Agent HTTP / sandbox | `gateway/web/`, `gateway/platforms/web_chat.py` |
| Sandboxed tools | `gateway/web/tools/` — **wrap upstream, never copy** |
| React UI | `web-chat/src/` |
| Deploy | `deploy/` |
| Platform tests | `tests/platform/` |
| Gateway tests | `tests/gateway/test_web_*.py` |

## Coding standards

- Minimize scope — smallest correct diff.
- Match surrounding style.
- Dependencies: pinned with upper bounds; `uv lock` after `pyproject.toml` changes.
- Paths: `get_hermes_home()` / `display_hermes_home()` — never hardcode `~/.hermes`.
- Users never touch shell, Docker, or config files — Web UI only.
